{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1537"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1537"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.18,0.71,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1537"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70751"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1263"},{"type":"tags","id":"3338"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5221"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"50032"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of his benign prostatic hyperplasia. He was diagnosed two years ago after experiencing urinary frequency, urgency and a weakened stream. His only medication is a combined dutasteride/tamsulosin tablet. He works as an accountant. He smokes 10 cigarettes daily and drinks 4-5 standard drinks daily. His BMI is 29 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft and non-tender without shifting dullness. There is no evidence of caput medusae, bruising or jaundice. The chest appearance is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the physical sign shown in the image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Morbid obesity","Old age","Alcohol misuse disorder","Dutasteride/tamsulosin","Adrenal tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with gynaecomastia, which is the development of breast tissue in males. It typically results from an excess of oestrogen or decreased androgen production, which may occur due to underlying pathology or medication effects. True gynaecomastia presents as a firm, disc-like mass of tissue beneath the nipple-areolar complex, distinct from the soft fatty tissue seen in pseudogynaecomastia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDutasteride/tamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause in this case. Dutasteride is a 5-alpha-reductase inhibitor that blocks the conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone. This hormonal manipulation can lead to an androgen-oestrogen imbalance, contributing to gynaecomastia development. This is a well-documented side effect occurring in approximately 1-2% of patients taking dutasteride.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol misuse disorder\u003C/strong\u003E can cause gynaecomastia through several mechanisms. Chronic alcohol use impairs testosterone synthesis in the testes and increases peripheral aromatization of androgens to oestrogens through alcoholic liver disease. While this patient drinks above recommended limits, he shows no clinical signs of advanced liver disease such as ascites, spider naevi, or caput medusae that would suggest this as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorbid obesity\u003C/strong\u003E (BMI \u003E40 kg/m2) is associated with gynaecomastia due to increased peripheral aromatization of androgens in adipose tissue. While this patient is overweight with a BMI of 29 kg/m2, this degree of adiposity alone would be unlikely to cause significant gynaecomastia. Additionally, obesity typically causes pseudogynaecomastia rather than true glandular gynaecomastia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOld age\u003C/strong\u003E related gynaecomastia typically occurs in men over 65 years due to age-related decline in testosterone production and increased peripheral aromatization. At 55 years, this patient is too young for this to be the primary cause. Age-related gynaecomastia is also usually bilateral and develops gradually over years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are a rare cause of gynaecomastia through increased oestrogen production or altered steroid metabolism. This diagnosis would be unlikely without other features of feminization such as decreased libido, testicular atrophy, or signs of Cushing syndrome. Additionally, adrenal tumours typically present with other symptoms such as hypertension or electrolyte abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gynaecomastia can be caused by 5-alpha-reductase inhibitors like dutasteride through suppression of dihydrotestosterone production","Common causes of gynaecomastia include medications, liver disease, obesity, and age-related hormonal changes","Physical examination should assess for signs of underlying systemic disease when evaluating gynaecomastia","True gynaecomastia presents as a firm, disc-like mass of tissue beneath the nipple-areolar complex"],"references":["Braunstein GD. Clinical practice. Gynecomastia. N Engl J Med. 2007 Sep 20;357(12):1229-37. doi: 10.1056/NEJMcp070677. PMID: 17881754.","Nguyen PL, Alibhai SM, Basaria S, D\u0027Amico AV, Kantoff PW, Keating NL, Penson DF, Rosario DJ, Tombal B, Smith MR. Adverse effects of androgen deprivation therapy and strategies to mitigate them. Eur Urol. 2015 May;67(5):825-36. doi: 10.1016/j.eururo.2014.07.010. Epub 2014 Aug 2. PMID: 25097095.","Gordon GG, Olivo J, Rafil F, Southren AL. Conversion of androgens to estrogens in cirrhosis of the liver. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 1975 Jun;40(6):1018-26. doi: 10.1210/jcem-40-6-1018. PMID: 1133151.","Moreno S, Guillermo M, Decoulx M, Dewailly D, Bresson R, Proye Ch. Feminizing adreno-cortical carcinomas in male adults. A dire prognosis. Three cases in a series of 801 adrenalectomies and review of the literature. Ann Endocrinol (Paris). 2006 Mar;67(1):32-8. doi: 10.1016/s0003-4266(06)72537-9. PMID: 16596055."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70751"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1537"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19959"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19959"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/171ad940-caed-4ba2-9fab-4c7dea455dea.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/171ad940-caed-4ba2-9fab-4c7dea455dea.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70751"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-21T22:52:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-21T22:54:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1537"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{